0–1930: The Prisoners’ Agenda for Prison Reform -- tGirls in Prison: The Role of the Buenos Aires Casa Correccional de Mujeres as an Institution for Child Rescue, 1890–1940 -- tRemembering Freedom: Life as Seen From the Prison Cell, Buenos Aires Province, 1930–1950 -- tAfterword -- tLaw and Society in Comparative Perspective -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCrowning a decade of innovative efforts in the historical study of law and legal phenomena in the region, Crime and Punishment in Latin America offers a collection of essays that deal with the multiple aspects of the relationship between ordinary people and the law. Building on a variety of methodological and theoretical trends—cultural history, subaltern studies, new political history, and others—the contributors share the conviction that law and legal phenomena are crucial elements in the formation and functioning of modern Latin American societies and, as such, need to be brought to the forefront of scholarly debates about the region’s past and present.While disassociating law from a strictly legalist approach, the volume showcases a number of highly original studies on topics such as the role of law in processes of state formation and social and political conflict, the resonance between legal and cultural phenomena, and the contested nature of law-enforcing discourses and practices. Treating law as an ambiguous and malleable arena of struggle, the contributors to this volume—scholars from North and Latin America who represent the new wave in legal history that has emerged in recent years-- demonstrate that law not only produces and reformulates culture, but also shapes and is shaped by larger processes of political, social, economic, and cultural change. In addition, they offer valuable insights about the ways in which legal systems and cultures in Latin America compare to those in England, Western Europe, and the United States.This volume will appeal to scholars in Latin American studies and to those interested in the social, cultural, and comparative history of law and legal phenomena.Contributors. Carlos Aguirre, Dain Borges, Lila Caimari, Arlene J. Díaz, Luis A. Gonzalez, Donna J. Guy, Douglas Hay, Gilbert M. Joseph, Juan Manuel Palacio, Diana Paton, Pablo Piccato, Cristina Rivera Garza, Kristin Ruggiero, Ricardo D. Salvatore, Charles F. Walker  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCrimezLatin AmericaxHistory. 0aJustice, Administration ofzLatin AmericaxHistory. 0aPunishmentzLatin AmericaxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aAguirre, Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAguirre, Carlos, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBorges, Dain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaimari, Lila M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDíaz, Arlene J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález, Luis A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuy, Donna J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHay, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoseph, Gilbert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoseph, Gilbert M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPalacio, Juan Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaton, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPiccato, Pablo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRivera-Garza, Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRug